  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Provision of Holistic Humanitarian Support to Persons With Disabilities in Aweil South and Tonj South</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">As a result of the conflict in South Sudan, it is estimated that the number of persons with disabilities increased substantially, including those with congenital disabilities or disability caused by mines, unexploded ordinance, the effects of war such as poverty, insufficient access to essential services, and displacement. IOM and Humanity and Inclusion (HI) surveys (Malakal 2021, Wau 2019, Bentiu 2018) on disability inclusion and access to humanitarian services in displacement camps shows that people with disabilities face greater challenges to access services, with greater challenges experienced among women and especially children with disabilities. There remain high levels of stigma and discrimination towards persons with disabilities, neurological and mental health conditions further reinforcing exclusion and vulnerability to protection and mental health risks. This project aims to improve empowerment and inclusion of persons with disabilities. In addition to focusing on the persons with disabilities, the project is reaching out through awareness raising activities to the wider community, among whom persons with disabilities reside. Inclusion of the broader community will assist in addressing the attitudinal and environmental barriers which persons with disabilities face in their day to day lives.</narrative>
  </description>
